  "en_notes_yusuf": [
    {
      "note_no": "402",
      "note": "In the abstract the People of the Book would agree to all three propositions. In practice they fail. Apart from doctrinal lapses from the unity of the One True God, there is the question of a consecrated Priesthood (among the Jews it was hereditary also), as if a mere human being-Cohen, or Pope, or Priest, or Brahman-could claim superiority apart from his learning and the purity of his life, or could stand between man and Allah in some special sense. The same remarks apply to the worship of saints. They may be pure and holy, but no one can protect us or claim Lordship over us except Allah. For Rabb, see 1:2, n. 20. Abraham was a true man of God, but he could not be called a Jew or a Christian as he lived long before the Law of Moses or the Gospel of Jesus was revealed."
    }
  ],
  "en_notes_asad": [
    {
      "note_no": "49",
      "note": "Lit., \"a word [that is] equitable between you and us\". The term kalimah, primarily meaning \"word\" or \"utterance\", is often used in the philosophical sense of \"proposition\" or \"tenet\"."
    },
    {
      "note_no": "50",
      "note": "Lit., \"that we shall not take one another for lords beside God\". Since the personal pronoun \"we\" obviously applies to human beings, the expression \"one another\" necessarily bears the same connotation. In its wider implication, the above call is addressed not merely to the Christians, who attribute divinity to Jesus and certain aspects of divinity to their saints, but also to the Jews, who assign a quasi-divine authority to Ezra and even to some of their great Talmudic scholars (cf. 9:30-31)."
    }
  ],
  "en_snotes_yusuf": "In the abstract the People of the Book would agree to all three propositions. In practice they fail. Apart from doctrinal lapses from the unity of the One True God, there is the question of a consecrated Priesthood (among the Jews it was hereditary also), as if a mere human being-Cohen, or Pope, or Priest, or Brahman-could claim superiority apart from his learning and the purity of his life, or could stand between man and Allah in some special sense. The same remarks apply to the worship of saints. They may be pure and holy, but no one can protect us or claim Lordship over us except Allah. For Rabb, see 1:2, n. 20. Abraham was a true man of God, but he could not be called a Jew or a Christian as he lived long before the Law of Moses or the Gospel of Jesus was revealed.",
  "en_snotes_asad": "Lit., \"a word [that is] equitable between you and us\". The term kalimah, primarily meaning \"word\" or \"utterance\", is often used in the philosophical sense of \"proposition\" or \"tenet\". Lit., \"that we shall not take one another for lords beside God\". Since the personal pronoun \"we\" obviously applies to human beings, the expression \"one another\" necessarily bears the same connotation. In its wider implication, the above call is addressed not merely to the Christians, who attribute divinity to Jesus and certain aspects of divinity to their saints, but also to the Jews, who assign a quasi-divine authority to Ezra and even to some of their great Talmudic scholars (cf. 9:30-31).",
